aerialway.en_description: Used for various forms of transport for passengers and goods that use wires, including cable-cars, chair-lifts and drag-lifts.

pylon.en_description: A pylon supporting the aerialway cable.

station.en_description: A station where passengers and/or goods can enter and/or leave the aerialway

chair_lift.en_description: An open chairlift run. These have a single seat to sit on and are open to the outside air.

drag_lift.en_description: An overhead tow-line for skiers and riders.

platter.en_description: An overhead tow-line for skiers and riders with platters.

t-bar.en_description: An overhead tow-line for skiers and riders with T-shaped carriers for two passengers.

goods.en_description: A cable supported lift for conveying goods, not passengers.

magic_carpet.en_description: A ski lift for small children resembling a conveyor belt.

zip_line.en_description: Zip line, gravity propelled aerial ropeslide like a flying fox or similar

gondola.en_description: An aerialway where the cabins go around in a circle.

rope_tow.en_description: A tow-line for skiers and riders where passenger hold by hand or use special tow grabbers.

mixed_lift.en_description: A mixed lift, containing both gondolas and chairs.

aeroway.en_description: For physical infrastructure used to support aircraft, air travel, spacecraft and space flight.

taxiway.en_description: A route where airplanes manouevre between runways and parking areas within an aerodrome

parking_position.en_description: A location where an airplane can park

runway.en_description: A strip of land on which aircraft can take off and land.

hangar.en_description: A large airport building with extensive floor areas for housing aircraft or spacecraft

helipad.en_description: A landing area or platform designed for helicopters

apron.en_description: An area of an airport where planes are parked, unloaded or loaded, refueled, or boarded

navigationaid.en_description: A facility that supports visual navigation for aircraft

holding_position.en_description: A point behind which aircraft are considered clear of a crossing way

gate.en_description: The bounded space, inside the airport terminal, where passengers wait before boarding their flight

windsock.en_description: An object that shows wind direction and speed.

jet_bridge.en_description: An enclosed, movable connector that extends from an airport terminal to an airplane

taxilane.en_description: A path for aircraft in an airport that is part of the aircraft parking area or apron

airstrip.en_description: A field or area where light aircraft can land and take off from.

stopway.en_description: A rectangular surface beyond the end of a runway used to support an aeroplane during an aborted takeoff.

tower.en_description: A tall, windowed structure common at airports used to control aircraft for take-off, landing, and ground movements.

heliport.en_description: A special aerodrome built for helicopters

holding_position_line.en_description: A line behind which aircraft are considered clear of a crossing way

aircraft_crossing.en_description: A point where the flow of traffic is impacted by crossing aircraft.

highway_strip.en_description: Designated emergency or military landing strip on an otherwise used highway

arresting_gear.en_description: A mechanical system used to rapidly decelerate an aircraft as it lands on a runway

spaceport.en_description: A spaceport or cosmodrome: a site for launching or receiving spacecraft

airtanker_base.en_description: A location to supply water and retardant to water bombers

control_center.en_description: A facility responsible for controlling aircraft en route in a particular volume of airspace (a Flight Information Region) at high altitudes between airport approaches and departures.

amenity.en_description: For describing useful and important facilities for visitors and residents.

bench.en_description: A place for people to sit; allows room for several people.

parking_space.en_description: A single parking space on a parking lot.

place_of_worship.en_description: A place where religious services are conducted.

restaurant.en_description: A restaurant sells full sit-down meals with servers, and may sell alcohol.

school.en_description: A primary or secondary school (pupils typically aged 6 to 18).

waste_basket.en_description: A single small container for depositing garbage that is easily accessible for pedestrians.

bicycle_parking.en_description: A parking space designed for bicycles.

fast_food.en_description: A place concentrating on very fast counter-only service and take-away food.

cafe.en_description: A generally informal place with sit-down facilities selling beverages and light meals and/or snacks.

fuel.en_description: A retail facility for refueling motor vehicles

shelter.en_description: A small structure for protection against bad weather conditions

recycling.en_description: A container or centre that accepts waste for recycling.

bank.en_description: A financial establishment where customers can, among other services, deposit money and take loans.

pharmacy.en_description: A shop where a pharmacist sells medications

post_box.en_description: A box to deposit outgoing postal items.

kindergarten.en_description: A place for looking after preschool children and (typically) giving early education.

drinking_water.en_description: A drinking water source which provides potable water for consumption.

vending_machine.en_description: A vending machine sells food, drinks, tickets or other goods automatically.

hunting_stand.en_description: An open or enclosed platform used by hunters to place themselves at an elevated height above the terrain.

bar.en_description: An establishment that sells alcoholic drinks to be consumed on the premises, characterised by a noisy and vibrant atmosphere. They usually do not sell food to be eaten as a meal. The music is usually loud and you often have to stand.

waste_disposal.en_description: A medium or large disposal bin, typically for bagged up household or industrial waste.

atm.en_description: A device that provides the clients of a financial institution with access to financial transactions.

hospital.en_description: A hospital providing in-patient medical treatment

post_office.en_description: A place where letters and parcels may be sent or collected.

pub.en_description: An establishment that sells alcoholic drinks that can be consumed on the premises, characterised by a traditional appearance and a relaxed atmosphere. Also sells food which also can be eaten on the premises. Customers can usually sit down at a table.

parking_entrance.en_description: A entrance to an underground or multi storey parking facility

clinic.en_description: A clinic is a medical centre, with more staff than a doctor's office, that does not admit inpatients.

grave_yard.en_description: A place where people (or sometimes animals) are buried, usually close to a place of worship.

community_centre.en_description: A place mostly used for local events, festivities and group activities.

doctors.en_description: A doctor's office, a place to get medical attention or a check up from a physician.

fountain.en_description: A fountain with cultural, decorational or historical significance or which serves a recreational purpose.

townhall.en_description: A townhall serves as a community administrative center or meeting place.

social_facility.en_description: A facility that provides social services

fire_station.en_description: A station from which a fire brigade operates.

charging_station.en_description: A location where an electric vehicle may be charged.

car_wash.en_description: A facility used to clean the exterior of motor vehicles

library.en_description: A place to read and/or lend books

marketplace.en_description: A marketplace where goods and services are traded daily or weekly.

college.en_description: A place for further education, a post-secondary education institution which is not a University

bus_station.en_description: A bus station would usually be a terminus where many routes stop / start, and where you can change between routes, etc.

bicycle_rental.en_description: A place, often unattended, where you can pick up and drop off rented bikes.

university.en_description: An educational institution designed for instruction, examination, or both, of students in many branches of advanced learning.

veterinary.en_description: A place that deals with the prevention, diagnosis and treatment of disease in animals.

childcare.en_description: A place where children are looked after which is not an amenity=kindergarten

ice_cream.en_description: A place that sells ice cream and/or frozen yoghurt over the counter.

theatre.en_description: A place where live theatrical performances are held.

parcel_locker.en_description: Machine for picking up and sending parcels.

water_point.en_description: A place where you can get large amounts of drinking water for refilling fresh water holding tanks.

bbq.en_description: A permanently built place for having a BBQ

motorcycle_parking.en_description: A place which is designated for parking motorcycles.

ferry_terminal.en_description: A place where people, cars etc. can board and leave a ferry.

cinema.en_description: A movie theater, a place showing movies.

shower.en_description: Public showers, where people can bathe under water sprays

grit_bin.en_description: A container that holds sand, salt and gravel to spread on roads for winter safety

driving_school.en_description: A school to learn to drive a motor vehicle

courthouse.en_description: A building which is home to a court of law, which administers justice according to the rule of law.

car_rental.en_description: A place from which cars can be rented.

arts_centre.en_description: An arts centre. A venue where a variety of arts are performed or conducted

nightclub.en_description: A place to dance and drink at night.

events_venue.en_description: A place that provides facilities for events such as banquets, weddings etc.

public_bookcase.en_description: A street furniture containing books. Take one, leave one.

letter_box.en_description: Private mailboxes where mailmen or other people deposit letters to specific addresses.

watering_place.en_description: A place where water is contained and animals such as horses can drink.

loading_dock.en_description: A loading dock is an entrance to a building used for loading and unloading goods vehicles.

bureau_de_change.en_description: An office that exchanges foreign currency and travellers cheques

bicycle_repair_station.en_description: A public tool for self-repair of bicycles.

prison.en_description: A prison or jail where people are incarcerated before trial or after conviction

food_court.en_description: A place with sit-down facilities shared by multiple self-service food vendors.

internet_cafe.en_description: A place whose principal role is providing internet services.

studio.en_description: A studio used for creating radio or television programmes and broadcasting them. It can also be used to mark a music recording studio.

nursing_home.en_description: A home for disabled/elderly persons who need permanent care.

mobile_money_agent.en_description: A place where mobile money can be payed in and out.

public_bath.en_description: A location where the public may bathe in common

biergarten.en_description: An open-air area where beer is served and you are allowed to bring your own food.

car_sharing.en_description: Carsharing station, where you get your booked car, often separate areas on parking places.

social_centre.en_description: A centre of fraternities, sororities, professional societies, union halls and other nonprofit organization.

vehicle_inspection.en_description: A place where legally-required vehicle inspection may be performed

music_school.en_description: Music school, an educational institution specialized in the study, training, and research of music

compressed_air.en_description: A device to inflate tires/tyres (e.g. motorcar, bicycle)

animal_breeding.en_description: A facility where animals are bred, usually to sell them

lavoir.en_description: A public place where people come to wash their clothes manually

monastery.en_description: An active monastery or convent, occupied by a community of monks or nuns living under religious vows

sanitary_dump_station.en_description: Place for depositing human waste from a toilet holding tank.

casino.en_description: A gambling venue with at least one table game.

waste_dump_site.en_description: A place where trash was illegally dumped.

money_transfer.en_description: A place that offers money transfers, especially cash to cash

lounger.en_description: An object for people to lie down.

language_school.en_description: An educational institution where one studies a foreign language

dojo.en_description: A formal training place for any of the Japanese do arts.

feeding_place.en_description: A place where animals are fed like a manger or an automated feeding station.

health_post.en_description: A village or neighborhood health post, without a permanent physician.

love_hotel.en_description: A love hotel is a type of short-stay hotel operated primarily for the purpose of allowing guests privacy for sexual activities.

research_institute.en_description: A research institute is an establishment endowed for doing research.

vacuum_cleaner.en_description: A device used to clean motor vehicles by vacuum.

ranger_station.en_description: An official park visitor facility with police, visitor information, permit services, etc.

training.en_description: Public place where you can get training.

post_depot.en_description: A distribution centre or sorting office for letters and parcels.

gambling.en_description: A place for gambling, not being a bookmaker, lottery shop, casino, or adult gaming centre.

driver_training.en_description: A place for driving training on a closed course

car_pooling.en_description: Car pooling station or spot, where you meet to get in (or where you get dropped off) someone's car or to pick up (or drop off) someone.

water.en_description: Using this tag is discouraged. Unclear meaning. There are different alternatives.

mortuary.en_description: A morgue or funeral home, used for the storage of human corpses

karaoke_box.en_description: A venue specifically for people to enjoy singing along with karaoke, usually with private booths.

chair.en_description: A chair which remains located in the same place.

animal_training.en_description: A facility used for non-competitive animal training

polling_station.en_description: A place where one can cast a ballot.

stage.en_description: A raised platform where performers perform.

kitchen.en_description: A public kitchen to use by everyone or customers/guests.

vehicle_ramp.en_description: A ramp for vehicle inspection and repairs.

dancing_school.en_description: A dancing school or dance studio

baking_oven.en_description: Describes public places that can be used for baking bread.

social_club.en_description: A working mans' club, with a private members bar,and other facilities

festival_grounds.en_description: A place dedicated for festivals - like song and dance festivals

marae.en_description: A communal meeting area used in Polynesian societies

give_box.en_description: A small facility where people drop off and pick up various types of items in the sense of free sharing and reuse.

music_venue.en_description: An indoor place to hear live music which is not a theatre

workshop.en_description: A room or building in which goods are manufactured or repaired

tuition.en_description: A supplementary school with a commercial-basis.

stool.en_description: A stool which remains located in the same place.

fence.en_description: A freestanding structure designed to restrict or prevent movement across a boundary, generally distinguished from a wall by the lightness of its construction.

gate.en_description: A section in a wall or fence which can be opened to allow access.

wall.en_description: A freestanding structure, designed to restrict or prevent movement across a boundary, typically made from solid brick, concrete or rocks, and almost always built so that it is opaque to vision.

hedge.en_description: A line of closely spaced shrubs and tree species, which form a barrier or mark the boundary of an area.

kerb.en_description: A stone edging to a pavement or raised path (right side is bottom, left side is top).

bollard.en_description: One or more solid (usually concrete or metal) pillar(s) used to control traffic.

retaining_wall.en_description: A structure that holds back soil or rock from a building, structure or area.

lift_gate.en_description: A bar or pole pivoted (rotates upwards to open) in such a way as to allow the boom to block vehicular access through a controlled point.

block.en_description: One or more large immobile block(s) usually barring free access along a way.

yes.en_description: Unspecific barrier value, it is always better to use more specific one if possible

guard_rail.en_description: A rail, typically metal, designed to keep vehicles within their roadway and prevent dangerous collisions

cycle_barrier.en_description: A barrier along a path that slows or prevents access for bicycle users.

toll_booth.en_description: A place where a road usage toll or fee is collected.

political.en_description: Political boundary, such as an electoral ward or parliamentary constituency

national_park.en_description: The boundary of a national park, an area of natural beauty, set aside for conservation and for recreation

place.en_description: The boundaries of a place , when these boundaries can be defined but these are not administrative boundaries

aboriginal_lands.en_description: Boundary of aboriginal/native/indigenous territories and reservations.

maritime.en_description: Maritime boundaries under the UN Convention on the Law of the Sea which are not administrative boundaries: the baseline, contiguous zone, and EEZ.

forest.en_description: A mostly wooded area with explicit boundaries

civil.en_description: A cultural boundary (for example ethnic), different from all official administrative boundaries

hazard.en_description: A designated hazardous area, with a potential source of damage to health, life, property, or any other interest of value

low_emission_zone.en_description: a geographically defined area which seeks to restrict or deter access by certain polluting vehicles with the aim of improving the air quality

statistical.en_description: An official boundary recognised by government for statistical purposes.

disputed.en_description: Tags used on boundaries that are disputed

water_protection_area.en_description: A water protection area to protect surface water and groundwater from contamination.

limited_traffic_zone.en_description: An area that requires authorization for the entry of certain vehicles, sometimes for specific periods.

special_economic_zone.en_description: A government-defined area in which the business and trade laws are different.

administrative_cooperation.en_description: Area where various administrative entities cooperate.

border_zone.en_description: Strip of land near the country border where special restrictions on movement apply

regional_park.en_description: Used for boundaries of different kinds of parks

national.en_description: unclear meaning, usage appears to be a mix of various mistakes

urban.en_description: It is the urban area of the "city / village" limited by the entrance/exit signs of the zone "traffic_sign=city_limit".

exclave.en_description: Part of territory surrounded by alien territory.

treaty.en_description: The boundary of the area of application of a treaty.

building.en_description: To mark the outline of a building, a man-made structure with a roof, standing more or less permanently in one place.

yes.en_description: A building of an unspecified type.

house.en_description: A single dwelling unit usually inhabited by one family.

residential.en_description: A general tag for a building constructed primarily for residential purposes.

detached.en_description: A detached house: a free-standing residential building usually housing a single family.

apartments.en_description: A building arranged into individual dwellings, often on separate floors. May also have retail outlets on the ground floor.

shed.en_description: A small, simple structure used as storage or workshop

industrial.en_description: A building constructed to house some manufacturing process

farm_auxiliary.en_description: A building on a farm that is not a dwelling.

roof.en_description: A building open on at least two sides.

terrace.en_description: The outline of a linear row of residential dwellings, each of which normally has its own entrance, which form a terrace ("row-house" or "townhouse" in North American English).

semidetached_house.en_description: A house that shares a common wall with another on one side.

commercial.en_description: A building constructed for non-specific commercial activities to take place there.

retail.en_description: A building primarily used for selling goods to the general public.

garages.en_description: A block of private garages each with a separate owner.

outbuilding.en_description: A less important building near to and on the same piece of land as a larger building

barn.en_description: An agricultural building that can be used for storage and as a covered workplace.

greenhouse.en_description: A building in which plants are grown

cabin.en_description: A small, roughly built house typically found in rural areas.

service.en_description: Service building usually is a small unmanned building with certain machinery (like pumps or transformers).

static_caravan.en_description: A mobile home (caravan) (semi)permanently left on a single site.

farm.en_description: A farmhouse is the main building of a farm

church.en_description: A building that was built as a church.

warehouse.en_description: A commercial building for storage of goods.

bungalow.en_description: Simple single-storey flat house, bungalow, holiday cottage

ruins.en_description: Frequently used to mark ruined buildings. However, this usage conflicts with general use of building tag. In theory it should only be used for buildings constructed to look like ruins.

carport.en_description: A carport is a covered structure used to offer limited protection to vehicles, primarily cars, from the elements.

allotment_house.en_description: A small outbuilding for short visits in a allotment garden

civic.en_description: A building hosting any civic amenity (town hall, library, swimming pool).

public.en_description: A building constructed as accessible to the general public (town hall, police station, court house).

hospital.en_description: A building which forms part of a hospital.

hotel.en_description: A building designed with separate rooms available for overnight accommodation.

manufacture.en_description: A building constructed to house some manufacturing process, see also tag:building=industrial.

ger.en_description: A portable, round tent (yurt or ger)

mosque.en_description: A building that was built as a mosque.

hangar.en_description: A hangar is a building used for the storage of aeroplanes, helicopters or space-craft.

dormitory.en_description: College or university dormitory for shared living of its students.

college.en_description: A building constructed to house a college.

stable.en_description: A building constructed as a stable for horses

silo.en_description: A silo is a building for storing bulk materials.

transformer_tower.en_description: A small but tall building constructed to comprise a transformer and connect to an overhead power line.

slurry_tank.en_description: A circular concrete structure holding liquid manure.

transportation.en_description: A building related to the public transportation.

sty.en_description: A building for raising domestic pigs.

temple.en_description: A building that was built as a temple

government.en_description: Building built to house government offices.

fire_station.en_description: A building constructed to house fire fighting equipment.

kiosk.en_description: A small one room retail building, with clients not entering the building.

grandstand.en_description: A grandstand at racecourse or sports ground.

houseboat.en_description: A boat (re)constructed as a floating home, staying at a single permanent location.

sports_centre.en_description: A building that was built as a sports centre

trullo.en_description: A stone hut with a conical roof, built without mortar

supermarket.en_description: A building built as a supermarket

pavilion.en_description: A building providing facilities for users of sports grounds

stilt_house.en_description: Stilt houses are houses raised on piles over the surface of the soil or a body of water.

stadium.en_description: A building which was built as stadium.

tent.en_description: A building mainly consisting of sheets of fabric or similar

digester.en_description: A building constructed as a digester, a bioreactor for the production of biogas from biomass.

sports_hall.en_description: A building that was built as a sports hall

container.en_description: A container used as a building.

religious.en_description: A building that was built as a religious building.

wayside_shrine.en_description: A wayside shrine that meets the criteria of a building.

bridge.en_description: A building used as a bridge.

tower.en_description: A tower, that is a building.

beach_hut.en_description: A beach hut: small, usually wooden, and often brightly coloured cabin or shelter above the high tide mark on popular bathing beaches.

conservatory.en_description: Conservatory - a building or room having glass or tarpaulin roofing and walls used as an indoor garden or a sunroom (winter garden).

military.en_description: An unspecific building constructed for military purposes.

factory.en_description: A building constructed as a factory.

shrine.en_description: A building that was built as a shrine

guardhouse.en_description: A small building constructed to house guard(s).

mobile_home.en_description: A mobile home, permanently located at the same location.

presbytery.en_description: A building that was built as a presbytery (where priests live and work).

cathedral.en_description: A building that was built as a cathedral

castle.en_description: A building constructed as a castle.

gatehouse.en_description: An entry control point building, spanning over a highway that enters a city or compound.

riding_hall.en_description: A building that was built as a riding hall or indoor arena

entrance.en_description: To mark the location of a building entrance.

glasshouse.en_description: A glass building in which plants are grown. Note far more popular building=greenhouse

barracks.en_description: A building built to house military personnel or laborers

synagogue.en_description: A building that was built as a synagogue.

livestock.en_description: A building or part of a building that was built for housing livestock

museum.en_description: A building which was designed as a museum.

ship.en_description: A decommissioned ship/submarine which stays in one place.

convent.en_description: A building constructed as a convent

tech_cab.en_description: Small prefabricated cabin structures for the air-conditioned accommodation of different technology.

bell_tower.en_description: Building constructed as a bell tower

windmill.en_description: A building constructed as a traditional windmill, historically used to mill grain with wind power.

brewery.en_description: building constructed as a brewery building

lighthouse.en_description: A lighthouse building - note that it is distinct from marking active light.

kingdom_hall.en_description: A building that was built as a meeting place for Jehovah's Witnesses.

porch.en_description: A porch is a covered area adjoining an entrance to a building and usually having a separate roof.

palace.en_description: A building constructed as a palace

marquee.en_description: A marquee is a tent or easily demountable tent-like building.

hall_of_residence.en_description: College or university dormitory for shared living of its students.

fire_lookout.en_description: A building originally built for fire spotting.

pagoda.en_description: A building constructed as a pagoda.

quonset_hut.en_description: A lightweight prefabricated structure in the shape of a semicircle.

bath.en_description: A building which was constructed as a bath.

tree_house.en_description: A building constructed around, next to or among the trunk or branches of one or more mature trees while above ground level.

font.en_description: The construction, built as a baptismal font.

ground_station.en_description: A building containing receiving devices to record information from satellites.

fort.en_description: A building constructed as a fort.

swimming_pool.en_description: A building which hosts swimming pool.

roundhouse.en_description: A characteristic semi-circular or circular building constructed to service engines

changing_rooms.en_description: A building designated for changing clothes.

smithy.en_description: Used for a building purpose-built to serve as a smithy or forge.

data_centre.en_description: A building used to house computers and network equipment.

venta.en_description: Typical Spanish inns generally located in unpopulated and remote rural areas.

gurdwara.en_description: A building that was built as a gurdwara

shepherd_shelter.en_description: A building for shepherds in cattle ranges

craft.en_description: A place producing or processing customized goods

grinding_mill.en_description: A device that breaks solid materials into smaller pieces by grinding, crushing, or cutting. The aftermath is powdered product, not liquid extract like oil mill.

carpenter.en_description: A workplace or office of carpenters that work with timber to construct, install and maintain buildings, furniture, and other objects.

metal_construction.en_description: Workplace or office of a person who work with metal. This applies to: planning, construction, trade, repair.

winery.en_description: A place where wine is produced

photographer.en_description: A workplace or office of a person who takes photographs using a camera.

electronics_repair.en_description: Repair shops and service centres which provides repair of computers, phones, appliance etc.

electrician.en_description: A person or company that works with electricity or electrical systems.

brewery.en_description: A dedicated building for the making of beer.

shoemaker.en_description: A place where shoes, boots, sandals, clogs and moccasins are created, repaired or altered to fit personal needs.

tailor.en_description: A place where clothing is made, repaired, or altered professionally, especially suits and men's clothing.

plumber.en_description: A workplace or office of a skilled tradesperson who specializes in (drinking) water supply, sewage and drainage systems

sawmill.en_description: A sawmill is a facility where logs are cut into timber

hvac.en_description: A workplace or office of an HVAC system designer (Heating, Ventilating, and Air Conditioning)

caterer.en_description: A workplace or office of one who prepares customized meals for takeout, or provides prepared meals or supplies to a group at social gatherings

window_construction.en_description: A workplace of someone constructing windows

confectionery.en_description: A place where the set of food items that are rich in sugar, any one or type of which is called a confection is produced.

dressmaker.en_description: Dressmaker is a person who makes custom clothing for women, such as dresses, blouses, and evening gowns.

gardener.en_description: A workplace or office of a garden designer or a landscape gardener.

handicraft.en_description: A place where useful and decorative devices are made completely by hand or using only simple tools

stonemason.en_description: A place where rough pieces of rock are shaped into accurate geometrical shapes.

glaziery.en_description: A place where residential, commercial, and artistic glass is selected, cut, installed, replaced, and removed.

painter.en_description: A workplace or office of a house painter which is a tradesman responsible for the painting and decorating of buildings.

joiner.en_description: An artisan who builds things by joining pieces of wood, particularly furniture or ornamental work.

builder.en_description: A workplace or office of a tradesman who performs structural alterations and additions to buildings.

roofer.en_description: A workplace or office of a tradesman who is specialized in roof covering and sealing.

key_cutter.en_description: A place where keys can be duplicated from originals.

upholsterer.en_description: A place where furniture, especially seats are provided with padding, springs, webbing, and fabric or leather covers.

blacksmith.en_description: A place where a blacksmith forges tools, horseshoes, etc. from iron.

pottery.en_description: A place where earthenware, stoneware and porcelain and other ceramic ware is made by potters.

distillery.en_description: An establishment for distilling, especially for distilling alcoholic liquors.

jeweller.en_description: A place where necklaces, rings, brooches, earrings and bracelets and other personal adornments are created or repaired.

cleaning.en_description: Workplace or office of a person who cleaning building, industrial facilities or windows.

agricultural_engines.en_description: A place where engines and tools for agricultural use are planned and constructed.

signmaker.en_description: A maker of signs, mainly for shops and other businesses.

locksmith.en_description: A place where locks and keys are created or repaired.

photographic_laboratory.en_description: A place where photos taken on a film or digital images are transformed into a more permanent form, often on paper or plastic foil.

tiler.en_description: A workplace or office of a person who lays tiles on floors, swimming pools and such.

watchmaker.en_description: A watchmaker is an artisan who makes and repairs watches. Today due to industrial production they mostly repair watches.

clockmaker.en_description: A workplace or office of a clockmaker that is building, repairing or engraving clocks of all sorts.

bakery.en_description: A workplace for fresh bakery goods. No shop.

printer.en_description: A small printing business which produces published works such as newspapers, books, magazines, etc.

welder.en_description: One who unites pieces of metal with high temperature.

tinsmith.en_description: A person who makes and repairs things made of light-coloured metal, particularly tinware.

floorer.en_description: A workplace or office of a floorer.

boatbuilder.en_description: A workplace where boats are planned and constructed

oil_mill.en_description: A mill designed to crush or bruise oil-bearing seeds, such as linseed or peanuts, or other oil-rich vegetable material.

optician.en_description: A place where lenses for the correction of a person's vision are designed, fitted and dispensed.

plasterer.en_description: A workplace or office of a tradesman who works with plaster, such as forming a layer of plaster on an interior wall or plaster decorative moldings on ceilings or walls.

bookbinder.en_description: A workplace for physically assembling a book from a number of sheets of paper.

scaffolder.en_description: A workplace or office of a tradesman who builds temporary structure used to support people and material in the construction or repair of buildings and other large structures.

cabinet_maker.en_description: A person who makes fine wooden furniture

saddler.en_description: A place where saddles or accessories for cars and boats are produced or repaired.

insulation.en_description: A workplace or office of a person who does thermal insulation in buildings.

atelier.en_description: A place where visual artists work

carpet_layer.en_description: A carpet layer is a tradesmen who specializes in laying carpets

dental_technician.en_description: A workplace for dental technician who constructs custom-made restorative and dental appliances

chimney_sweeper.en_description: A workplace or office of a person who cleans chimneys for a living.

sun_protection.en_description: A place where sun protection is made, repaired, or delivered for assembly, especially awnings and shutters.

printmaker.en_description: A producer of fine art prints.

parquet_layer.en_description: A workplace or office of a parquet layer.

cheese.en_description: Dedicated to the making of cheese.

sailmaker.en_description: A workshop of a sailmaker who cleans, repairs and makes sails.

turner.en_description: A workplace or office of a turner.

toolmaker.en_description: A workplace of a company that builds complex tools, machine tools, moulds, gauges,... .

car_painter.en_description: A place specializing in painting cars.

goldsmith.en_description: The workplace of a person who forges things out of gold, especially jewelry.

luthier.en_description: Workshop of a luthier, who makes or repairs stringed wooden musical instruments, such as lutes, violins, and guitars.

engraver.en_description: A workplace or office of an engraver.

organ_builder.en_description: Organ building is the profession of designing, building, restoring and maintaining pipe organs.

pest_control.en_description: A business that offers pest control services

tatami.en_description: A workplace or office of an artisan for tatami mat.

rigger.en_description: The workplace of a person who sets up the rigging for sailboats and sailing ships (or possibly a person who works on ropes, booms, lifts, hoists and the like for a stage production)

interior_work.en_description: Workplace or office of a person who build non-load-bearing interior walls, especially drywall.

door_construction.en_description: A workplace of someone constructing doors

paver.en_description: The workshop or office of a paver

weaver.en_description: Workshop of a person producing something by weaving, may offer products for sale

glassblower.en_description: A person or company that blows bottles or other objects from molten glass.

stand_builder.en_description: A workplace of a company that builds stands/booths for fairs.

carpet_cleaner.en_description: A carpet cleaner is a tradesman who specializes in cleaning carpets

stove_fitter.en_description: A workplace/office of a person / company who designs and builds stoves / tiled stoves.

piano_tuner.en_description: A piano tuner or technician. A professional that tunes, regulates and makes the maintenance of pianos. Most of them repair simple problems and some restore a whole piano.

water_well_drilling.en_description: A company that drills water wells.

information_electronics.en_description: Workplace or office of an information electronics which is a tradesman specialized repairing Television, Radio, monitors, and other electronic components, they build roof aerial, rooftop dish, networks in buildings and more.

cooper.en_description: A person or company that manufacture of containers and vessels mainly made of wood.

candlemaker.en_description: A person who makes candles or a manufactory where candles were made

mint.en_description: A place where coins and medals are hand crafted.

bag_repair.en_description: A place where bags/luggage are repaired.

yes.en_description: Indicates either that a road is accessible to emergency vehicles or that a hospital is equipped to deal with emergencies.

ladder_site.en_description: An installation area for fire engines

rescue_box.en_description: A box in a mountain or wilderness area, containing a stretcher and first-aid materials

fire_sand_bin.en_description: A fire sand storage bin designed for the bulk storage of fire sand.

standpipe.en_description: A standpipe without a Siamese connection.

throw_bag.en_description: A rope in a bag to throw out to someone who is struggling in water.

shower.en_description: A shower for use in emergency situations

fire_blanket.en_description: This tag is used to describe fire blankets.

rescue_buoy.en_description: A rope in a bag to throw out to someone who is struggling in water.

meteor_crater.en_description: A crater formed by the impact of a meteor.

hoodoo.en_description: A column of rock with a hat

service.en_description: Generally for access to a building, service station, beach, campsite, industrial estate, business park, etc.

footway.en_description: A path mainly or exclusively for pedestrians.

street_lamp.en_description: A single pole with one or more lights to illuminate the street.

trunk.en_description: Important roads that are not motorways.

give_way.en_description: Used to mark give way (also known as yield) signs or markings

tertiary_link.en_description: Connecting slip roads/ramps of tertiary highways

yes.en_description: Used to add the historic significance of the objects described by other tags.

boundary_stone.en_description: A historic physical marker that identifies a boundary

monument.en_description: A memorial object, which is especially large, built to remember, show respect to a person or group of people or to commemorate an event.

tomb.en_description: A structure where somebody has been buried.

castle.en_description: Used for various kinds of castles, palaces, fortresses, manors, stately homes, kremlins, shiros and other.

charcoal_pile.en_description: Historic site of a charcoal pile. Often still in good condition in hilly forest areas.

citywalls.en_description: A citywall is a fortification used to defend a city.

manor.en_description: Historic manors/mansions having different use today

heritage.en_description: A building/area/site/monument officially recognized for its historic or cultural value.

church.en_description: A church with a historical value.

milestone.en_description: A historic marker that shows the distance to important destinations

city_gate.en_description: A city gate within a city wall

wreck.en_description: A nautical craft that has been sunk or destroyed.

cannon.en_description: A historic/retired cannon. Usually found on forts or battlefields.

stone.en_description: A stone shaped or placed by man with historical value.

aircraft.en_description: A decommissioned aircraft which generally remains in one place.

farm.en_description: A historical farm, kept in its original state.

tower.en_description: This property distinguishes a tower as historic

monastery.en_description: Building/place that is a historically significant monastery.

battlefield.en_description: The site of a battle or military skirmish in the past.

locomotive.en_description: A decommissioned locomotive which generally remains in one place

road.en_description: A road or street that is of historical importance.

aqueduct.en_description: A historic structure to convey water

ship.en_description: A decommissioned ship/submarine which generally remains in one place

tank.en_description: A decommissioned tank which generally remains in one place

railway_car.en_description: A decommissioned railway car which generally remains in one place

castle_wall.en_description: A fortification surrounding the bailey of a castle

rune_stone.en_description: Stones, boulders or bedrock with historical runic inscriptions.

vehicle.en_description: A decommissioned vehicle which generally remains in one place

folly.en_description: Folly is a building constructed primarily for decoration, but suggesting through its appearance some other purpose.

highwater_mark.en_description: A marker indicating a past flood or high water.

tree_shrine.en_description: A tree with a religious image on it

anchor.en_description: A historic/retired anchor. Usually found in historic maritime areas.

mosque.en_description: A mosque with a historical and archaeological value.

ste\u0107ak.en_description: Specifies megalithic gravestone from medieval Bosnia

mass_path.en_description: Use on relations to combine highways into a mass path.

market_cross.en_description: A cross marking a market place, sometimes moved to a new location.

missile.en_description: An unused and unarmed missile which generally remains in one place.

pitch.en_description: An area designed for practising a particular sport, normally designated with appropriate markings.

garden.en_description: A place where flowers and other plants are grown in a decorative and structured manner or for scientific purposes.

playground.en_description: A playground: an area designed for children to play.

picnic_table.en_description: A table with benches for food and rest

sports_centre.en_description: A sports centre is a distinct facility where sports take place within an enclosed area.

track.en_description: A track for running, cycling and other non-motorised racing such as horses, greyhounds.

fitness_centre.en_description: Fitness centre, health club or gym with exercise machines, fitness classes or both, for exercise.

fitness_station.en_description: An outdoor facility where people can practise typical fitness exercises

slipway.en_description: A slipway: a ramp for launching a boat into water

stadium.en_description: A major sports facility with substantial tiered seating.

outdoor_seating.en_description: A seating area, usually for the consumption of food and drink from neighbouring cafes and restaurants, often belonging to one or more of them, but not necessarily adjacent.

bleachers.en_description: Raised, tiered rows of benches found at spectator events

firepit.en_description: A fire ring or fire pit, often at a campsite or picnic site

common.en_description: Identify land over which the public has general rights of use for certain leisure activities.

marina.en_description: A facility for mooring leisure yachts and motor boats.

sports_hall.en_description: A sufficiently large single room that is suitable for practising sports indoors and does not have a "centre" character.

dog_park.en_description: A designated area, with or without a fenced boundary, where dog-owners are permitted to exercise their pets unrestrained.

resort.en_description: A place used for relaxation or recreation, attracting visitors for vacations, tourism and/or going swimming in a pool and/or a nearby body of water.

fishing.en_description: A public or private place for fishing

sauna.en_description: A room or object designed as a place to dry a wet or dry body.

dance.en_description: A dance venue or dance hall.

ice_rink.en_description: A place where you can skate and play bandy or ice hockey.

bird_hide.en_description: A place that is used to observe wildlife, especially birds.

swimming_area.en_description: An official open-space natural place where you can swim

schoolyard.en_description: Outdoor area for spending school breaks.

summer_camp.en_description: A place for supervised camps for children or teenagers conducted during the summer months

indoor_play.en_description: A indoor play area, offering play facilities and event hosting for children.

trampoline_park.en_description: A leisure facility consisting of many interlinked trampolines

bathing_place.en_description: Public place where you can freely bath in nature.

barefoot.en_description: Specifies that a path is specifically designed for people to walk barefoot.

shooting_ground.en_description: A place where shooting enthusiasts can practice a range of disciplines.

maze.en_description: An area filled with footways that are separated by walls, hedges, corn plants, or other barriers.

practice_pitch.en_description: A small place set up for practicing a given sport, but not appropriate for a full game

music_venue.en_description: An indoor place to hear live music which is not a theatre.

axe_throwing.en_description: A facility equipped to play the game of axe throwing.

sunbathing.en_description: A designated outdoor place for sunbathing

soccer_golf.en_description: A place or area where you can play soccer golf.

events.en_description: A place that provides facilities for events such as banquets, weddings etc.

picnic.en_description: An area set aside for casual outdoor eating.

festival_grounds.en_description: A place dedicated for festivals - like song and dance festivals

bingo_hall.en_description: An establishment for playing in game of bingo.

club_house.en_description: The location that is almost exclusively used, and normally owned or operated, by a club.

foot_bath.en_description: A foot bath is a shallow pool, often with handrail.

storage_tank.en_description: A container that holds liquids or compressed gases.

tower.en_description: A tower is a free-standing structure which is higher than it is wide.

survey_point.en_description: A triangulation pillar, geodetic vertex, or other piece of fixed equipment used by topographers.

cutline.en_description: A straight line cut in a forest.

bridge.en_description: The outline of a bridge, grouping together all features for that bridge.

works.en_description: A factory or industrial production plant

cross.en_description: Cross, especially one with little historical value

lighthouse.en_description: Tower that emits light to serve as a navigational aid at sea or on inland waterway

lamp.en_description: A lamp, which may be a street lamp, a floodlight, a signal lamp or any other type of lamp.

avalanche_protection.en_description: A feature to protect from avalanches or to keep them from going off.

windmill.en_description: A traditional windmill, historically used to mill grain with wind power.

watermill.en_description: A mill driven by water power.

flare.en_description: A tower constructed to burn off excess gas.

cairn.en_description: A mound of stones, usually conical or pyramidal, raised as a landmark or to designate a point of importance in surveying.

dolphin.en_description: A marine structure for berthing and mooring of vessels.

beacon.en_description: A structure for signalling on land and sea

spoil_heap.en_description: Spoil heap, piles of waste rock removed during mining

quay.en_description: A man-made structure alongside navigable water used for loading and unloading vessels.

communications_tower.en_description: A huge tower for transmitting radio applications

telescope.en_description: Telescope: an instrument that aids in the observation of remote objects by collecting light or radio waves

offshore_platform.en_description: Offshore platform, oil platform or offshore drilling rig

excavation.en_description: Man made hole in the ground.

basin.en_description: An area of land artificially graded to hold water.

pump.en_description: A device in charge of moving or raising the level of liquids.

carpet_hanger.en_description: A construction to hang carpets for cleaning with the help of carpet beaters.

guy_wire.en_description: Defines a guy wire for a mast

threshing_floor.en_description: An open air paved area created to thresh the grain harvest and then winnow it.

chiller.en_description: industrial cooling construction with large diameter fans

clarifier.en_description: A clarifier of a wastewater treatment plant.

stupa.en_description: A Buddhist dome-shaped structure with a spire on top

nesting_site.en_description: A man made nesting aid that is mounted on a support device.

frost_fan.en_description: A device to stop frosts from damaging crops

drinking_fountain.en_description: Provides a small jet of drinking water.

compass_rose.en_description: A compass rose or wind rose.

video_wall.en_description: A digital screen, typically constructed out of smaller LED panels.

fuel_pump.en_description: A fuel pump (petrol pump, gas pump)

ski_jump.en_description: The man made in-run structure/tower of a ski jumping hill

outfall.en_description: A discharge point of a drain, sewer, or other stream into a watercourse or other body of water.

paifang.en_description: A traditional style of Chinese architectural arch or gateway structure.

oxidation_ditch.en_description: An oxidation ditch of a wastewater treatment plant.

foundation.en_description: A foundation of a building, without building itself.

sewer_vent.en_description: Used to map sewer vent pipes.

ice_house.en_description: A dug or built structure to hold ice.

tell.en_description: Man made mount created by years of inhabitation. A common archaeological feature of the Near & Middle East.

snow_net.en_description: A netting fence built across steep slopes to reduce risk and severity of (snow) avalanches

footwear_decontamination.en_description: A facility to decontaminate footwear for hikers.

clothes_line.en_description: A device for drying your clothes

urine_deflector.en_description: Sloped structures found in corners or along walls to prevent people urinating.

mounting_block.en_description: An aid to mounting a horse, usually with steps

loudspeaker.en_description: A device designed to sound transmission through air for the benefit of the community.

guy.en_description: A rope used for tighting a structure, like a mast

duck_decoy.en_description: A duck decoy is a structure for catching ducks and other waterfowl.

aircraft.en_description: A decommissioned aircraft which generally remains in one place.

bird_perch.en_description: A man made bird perch intended for birds of prey that is mounted on a support device.

desalination_plant.en_description: A plant for obtaining drinking water or process water from salt water (seawater) by reducing the salt content.

academy.en_description: A training establishment for military service members

religion.en_description: office of a community of faith

research.en_description: An office for research and development

charity.en_description: An office of a charitable organization

guide.en_description: An office of tour guides, mountain guides, hiking guides, dive guides, etc.

parish.en_description: Consider using the more used office=religion instead.

medical.en_description: An unspecified medical office - consider more specific tags instead

healthcare.en_description: An office of the health-care company.

private_investigator.en_description: An office of a private investigator

visa.en_description: An office of an organisation or business which offers visa assistance

interior_design.en_description: An office for an interior designer or group of interior designers.

tax.en_description: Fiscal authorities, tax and revenue office or a tax advisor.

tutoring.en_description: An office of tutor or tutoring centre.

wedding_planner.en_description: An office of a wedding planner

reception.en_description: A reception office of a campsite, business center or other place.

school.en_description: An office for a certain subdomain of a school.

rental.en_description: An office that rents different kinds vehicles or (sport) equipment.

place.en_description: Defines the center or outline of a named place

billiards.en_description: Cue sports, a wide variety of games of skill generally played with a cue stick which is used to strike billiard balls, moving them around a cloth-covered billiards table bounded by rubber cushions.

horseshoes.en_description: Throwing horseshoes at a peg target.

rugby_league.en_description: A ball game using both feet and hands between two teams.

tetherball.en_description: Tetherball is a game where two players use their hands to strike a volleyball which is suspended from stationary metal pole by a rope or tether.

shuffleboard.en_description: Shuffleboard is a game in which players use cues to push weighted discs, with the purpose of having them come to rest within a marked scoring area.

roller_skating.en_description: The travelling on surfaces with roller skates.

climbing_adventure.en_description: An Adventure Park, where people climb, walk or otherwise move on prebuilt wires and other objects.

rowing.en_description: Additional tag added on object to mark them as used for sport of rowing

sailing.en_description: Sailing: the sport of using wind to power sails which propel a boat

9pin.en_description: A bowling game played in Europe with only 9 pins.

bullfighting.en_description: Bullfighting, both on foot and on horseback, is a physical contest in which bulls are fought by humans.

paintball.en_description: A game in which players mark their opponents with colored paint capsules shot out of an air gun.

long_jump.en_description: An athletic discipline in which athletes attempt to leap as far as possible from a take off point

american_handball.en_description: Tag used to mark features as used for american handball

ice_stock.en_description: Ice stock sport, also known as Bavarian curling, is a winter sport, somewhat similar to curling. In German, it is known as Eisstockschießen.

boxing.en_description: Boxing is a combat sport in which two people engage in a contest by throwing punches with gloved hands against each other.

trampoline.en_description: Trampolining is a sport that is carried out on large trampolines indoor or outdoors

racquet.en_description: Racquetball is a racquet sport played with a hollow rubber ball

surfing.en_description: Person riding a wave using a board.

martial_arts.en_description: Codified systems and traditions of combat practices

paddle_tennis.en_description: Paddle tennis is a racquet sport adapted from tennis and played for over a century.

miniature_golf.en_description: Miniature golf, also known as minigolf, mini-putt, crazy golf, or putt-putt, is an offshoot of the sport of golf focusing solely on the putting aspect of its parent game.

ski_jumping.en_description: Ski jumping is a winter sport in which competitors aim to achieve the longest jump after descending from a specially designed ramp on their skis.

five-a-side.en_description: A variation of soccer with only 5 persons per team on a smaller pitch

pilates.en_description: Pilates is a physical fitness system developed in the early 20th century by Joseph Pilates.

squash.en_description: Squash is a racket and ball sport played by two or four players in a four-walled court with a small, hollow rubber ball.

korfball.en_description: Korfball: a team sport played with a ball on a rectangular court

toboggan.en_description: Added on toboggan runs, toboggan sport shops etc

croquet.en_description: A sport or game that is played between two or more players embedded on a small grass playing court or pitch which involves hitting plastic or wooden balls with a mallet through hoops (often called "wickets" in the United States).

curling.en_description: A sport in which players slide stones on a sheet of ice towards a target area which is segmented into four concentric rings.

lacrosse.en_description: A team sport played with a lacrosse stick and a lacrosse ball. Players use the head of the lacrosse stick to carry pass, catch, and shoot the ball into the goal.

judo.en_description: Judo: a modern Japanese martial art, combat and Olympic sport.

dog_racing.en_description: A feature used for dog racing

water_ski.en_description: Person on a board pulled over water by a boat or cable.

gaga.en_description: Gaga (or gaga ball) is a variant of dodgeball that is played in a gaga "pit"

table_soccer.en_description: Table Soccer or Table Football, also known as Foosball, Fussball, Kicker, or Tecball, is a table-top game and sport based off association football (soccer).

batting_cage.en_description: A batting cage is an area where you practice batting or catching.

kitesurfing.en_description: Property added to a sports facility to mark as used for kitesurfing

cockfighting.en_description: A blood sport between two roosters (cocks), or more accurately gamecocks, held in a ring called a cockpit.

laser_tag.en_description: Laser tag is a tag game played in an arena.

canadian_football.en_description: A sport played by two teams of 12 players on a rectangular field with goal posts at each end.

shot-put.en_description: Shot-put is a sport involving throwing a heavy spherical object as far as possible.

fencing.en_description: Fencing is the martial art of fighting with blades. Divided into three weapon categories: foil, sabre (spelled saber in the United States) and épée.

biathlon.en_description: The biathlon is a winter sport that combines cross-country skiing and rifle shooting.

aikido.en_description: A Japanese martial art by blending with the motion of the attacker and redirecting the force of the attack rather than opposing it head-on.

horse_riding.en_description: Ambigous tag for horse related sports

darts.en_description: Darts is a form of throwing game in which small missiles are thrown at a circular target (dartboard) fixed to a wall.

calisthenics.en_description: Form of exercise consisting of a variety of exercises that uses the body's own weight as the load.

obstacle_course.en_description: A series of challenging physical obstacles an individual or team must navigate, usually while being timed.

wakeboarding.en_description: Wakeboarding is a water sport in which the rider, standing on a wakeboard, is towed behind a motorboat in order to perform aerial maneuvers.

bowling.en_description: A bowling. Please use sport=9pin or sport=10pin instead.

parkour.en_description: Parkour is a training discipline using movement that developed from military obstacle course training.

bobsleigh.en_description: A winter sport in which teams of two or four make timed runs down narrow, twisting, banked, iced tracks in a gravity-powered sled, also called luge or bobslede.

kickboxing.en_description: Kickboxing is a group of stand-up combat sports based on kicking and punching.

snooker.en_description: Snooker is a cue sport that is played on a rectangular table covered with a green cloth with pockets at each of the four corners and in the middle of each long side.

cliff_diving.en_description: Non-competitive diving is jumping from a cliff or a rock into water.

pes\u00e4pallo.en_description: Pesäpallo, sometimes known as Finnish baseball, is a fast-moving bat-and-ball sport where the offense tries to score by hitting the ball successfully and running through the bases, while the defense tries to put the batter and runners out.

dog_agility.en_description: Dog agility is a dog sport in which a handler directs a dog through an obstacle course in a race for both time and accuracy.

speedway.en_description: Motorcycle speedway, usually referred to as speedway, is a motorcycle sport involving four and sometimes up to six riders competing over four anti-clockwise laps of an oval circuit.

water_sports.en_description: Sport activities conducted in or on waterbodies.

nine_mens_morris.en_description: Nine Men's Morris is a popular two-player strategy board game.

krachtbal.en_description: Team sport played with a heavy ball on a rectangular pitch, originating in West-Flanders, Belgium

bandy.en_description: Bandy is a sport played by two teams of eleven players on a rectangular field.

sumo.en_description: A traditional martial arts sport of Japan.

floorball.en_description: Floorball is a type of floor hockey with five players and a goalkeeper in each team.

bodybuilding.en_description: Develop one's muscles via hypertrophy for aesthetic purposes

pole_dance.en_description: Pole dance as kind of sport

footballgolf.en_description: Footballgolf, also known as soccergolf or just footgolf is a sport similar to golf, but played with a football which is kicked around the course.

water_polo.en_description: A competitive ball sport played in a pool between two teams.

ultimate.en_description: Ultimate, also known as ultimate frisbee, is a team sport played with a flying disc (frisbee).

8pin.en_description: Bowling game played in France in department of Aveyron and some places in Paris with only 8 pins

petanque.en_description: Using this tag is discouraged, use tag:sport=boules + tag:boules=petanque instead.

canoe_polo.en_description: Canoe Polo, also known as Kayak Polo, is one of the competitive disciplines of canoeing

hapkido.en_description: A dynamic and highly eclectic Korean martial art

hiking.en_description: Going for a long, vigorous walk, usually on trails or footpaths in the countryside.

barre.en_description: Fitness improvement using a ballet barre.

trugo.en_description: A game which involves hitting a rubber ring with a wooden mallet to a goal on a grass pitch.

fives.en_description: Fives is a ball game played as singles or double with affinity to squash.

candlepin.en_description: A variation of bowling that is played primarily in the Canadian Maritime provinces and the New England states of the United States.

base.en_description: BASE jumping is an activity that employs an initially packed parachute to jump from fixed objects.

cycle_ball.en_description: A cycle ball. Similar to association football played on bicycles.

tourism.en_description: A place or object of specific interest to tourists.

information.en_description: Information for tourists and visitors, including information offices

hotel.en_description: Hotel – an establishment that provides paid lodging

attraction.en_description: An object of interest for a tourist, or a purpose-built tourist attraction

viewpoint.en_description: A place worth visiting, often high, with a good view of surrounding countryside or notable buildings.

guest_house.en_description: Accommodation smaller than a hotel and typically owner-operated, such as bed&breakfasts etc.

picnic_site.en_description: A locality that is suitable for outdoors eating, with facilities to aid a picnic such as tables and benches

camp_site.en_description: An area where people can camp overnight using tents, camper vans, or caravans.

museum.en_description: A museum: an institution with exhibitions on scientific, historical, cultural topics

chalet.en_description: A holiday cottage with self-contained cooking and bathroom facilities.

apartment.en_description: A furnished apartment or flat with cooking and bathroom facilities that can be rented for holiday vacations.

camp_pitch.en_description: A tent or caravan pitch location within a campsite or caravan site

motel.en_description: Short term accommodation, particularly for people travelling by car.

caravan_site.en_description: A place where you can stay in a caravan overnight or for longer periods.

gallery.en_description: An area or building that displays a variety of visual art exhibitions.

wilderness_hut.en_description: A remote building, with generally a fireplace, intended to provide temporary shelter and sleeping accommodation, typically un-serviced and with no staff.

alpine_hut.en_description: A remote building located in the mountains intended to provide board and lodging.

theme_park.en_description: An amusement park where entertainment is provided by rides, games, concessions.

zoo.en_description: A zoological garden, where animals are confined for viewing by the public.

aquarium.en_description: A facility with living aquatic animals for public viewing.

wine_cellar.en_description: A wine cellar, a storage room for wine in bottles or barrels.

resort.en_description: A place used for relaxation or recreation, attracting visitors for vacations, tourism and/or going swimming in a pool and/or a nearby body of water.

hunting_lodge.en_description: Small country property specifically used for organising hunting parties

spa_resort.en_description: Establishment offering relaxing treatment for health and beauty, the types that are called spa-treatments. Should involve some kind of bathing.

waterway.en_description: Used to mark rivers or other kind of waterways.

stream.en_description: A naturally-forming waterway that is too narrow to be classed as a river.

ditch.en_description: A small man-made drainage waterway, usually unlined.

river.en_description: The linear flow of a river, in flow direction.

drain.en_description: An artificial free flow waterway used for carrying superfluous water, usually lined with concrete.

canal.en_description: An artificial '''open flow''' waterway used to carry useful water for transportation, waterpower, or irrigation.

dam.en_description: A barrier built across a river or stream to block and regulate the flow of the river.

weir.en_description: A barrier built across a river to control water speed and depth. Designed to let water flow over the top all the time or at least in specific conditions.

waterfall.en_description: A place where water flows over a vertical drop or a series of drops in the course of a stream or river.

rapids.en_description: A fast-flowing and turbulent section of a waterway which is not a waterfall.

drystream.en_description: A negative form of erosion relief formed by the activity of temporary streams.

artificial.en_description: Tag used in poorly done import, despite high usage is not used in real mapping.

pressurised.en_description: An artificial waterway where water flows in a closed space without air

tidal_channel.en_description: A natural intertidal waterway in mangroves, salt marshes, and tidal flats with water flow in the direction of the tide.

dock.en_description: An enclosed area for ships or boats within which the height of the water can be managed, or a dry dock.

milestone.en_description: A landmark of stone or metal to indicate the distance traveled along a watercourse.

boatyard.en_description: A place for constructing, repairing and storing vessels out of the water.

soakhole.en_description: The point at which a river or stream percolates into or through the soil

stream_end.en_description: The natural end of a stream (where it seeps into the ground).

fairway.en_description: A navigable route in a lake or sea, often marked by buoys or beacons.

fish_pass.en_description: A fish pass, also known as a fish ladder, a fishway or fish steps, is a structure on or around artificial barriers (such as dams and locks) to facilitate diadromous fishes natural migration.

sluice_gate.en_description: A movable gate to control water flow

derelict_canal.en_description: A derelict artificial open waterway used for transportation, waterpower, or irrigation.

fuel.en_description: A place to get fuel for boats

brook.en_description: Tiny waterway, often, but not always, dry part of the year.

riverbank.en_description: Use of this tag is discouraged, see natural=water + water=river instead

turning_point.en_description: A place to turn the driving direction for vessels, where the boats are longer than the river/canal is wide.

water_point.en_description: A place to fill fresh water holding tanks of a boat.

sanitary_dump_station.en_description: Marine facility for depositing human waste from a toilet holding tank.

flow_control.en_description: A flow control device on the waterway.

floating_barrier.en_description: A connected line of floats across the surface of a body of water which prevents passage of watercraft or debris.

spillway.en_description: A structure allowing the controlled release of water from a waterbody (reservoir, canal, river)

portage.en_description: Virtual extension of a portage to its waterbodies centerline

dredged_area.en_description: Area dredged to maintain a certain minimum depth

canoe_pass.en_description: A passage made for whitewater praticants to cross dam/weir, staying in the boat.
